      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's highly unlikely that the Wi-Fi network name is being used to suggest surveillance or tracking. The name is simply the title of your neighbor's Wi-Fi network. Modern Wi-Fi networks do not have the capability to track the physical movements of individuals inside a home without additional hardware and significantly more complex technology, which isn't typically in common use by Wi-Fi users.\n\nThe phenomenon you're describing might just be how Wi-Fi signals cover different parts of a house and appear stronger in certain locations. It's natural for your neighbor's Wi-Fi signal to be more consistent in some rooms as the Wi-Fi device might be nearer to the router, or the structure of the house could be causing signal reflection or absorption that favors other areas.\n\nIf you're concerned about your personal privacy, ensure your own Wi-Fi network is secure. Change your password, keep it updated, and enable features like network encryption and MAC address filtering if you feel the need for added security. Remember, the usual functioning of a Wi-Fi network does not involve tracking individuals and there are no established consumer technologies that allow one person's Wi-Fi signal to actively monitor someone like yourself inside your home.",
